### nextTick vs setImmediate

`process.nextTick()` executes callbacks in the nextTick queue, before any I/O events. `setImmediate()` executes callbacks in the check phase, after I/O events. The execution order is: nextTick queue → microtasks (promises) → timers → I/O → check phase (setImmediate).

Use `nextTick()` when you need to defer work until after current operation completes but before I/O. Use `setImmediate()` for long-running CPU tasks to prevent blocking I/O.

```typescript
setImmediate(() => console.log('setImmediate 1'));
process.nextTick(() => console.log('nextTick 1'));
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('promise'));
setImmediate(() => console.log('setImmediate 2'));
process.nextTick(() => console.log('nextTick 2'));

// Output order:
// nextTick 1
// nextTick 2
// promise
// setImmediate 1
// setImmediate 2
```


**Common interview trap:** Candidates confuse the execution order. nextTick always runs before setImmediate, regardless of declaration order.

