### Node.js Clustering: IPC, Sticky Sessions, and the Master/Worker Protocol

The cluster module forks `numCPUs` worker processes that all share the same TCP port. The OS kernel distributes incoming connections across workers (round-robin on Linux, OS-assigned on others). Workers are independent Node.js processes with separate memory — no shared state.

The hidden problem: **sticky sessions**. If a user's first request lands on worker 1 and creates an in-memory session, their next request may land on worker 3 — session not found. Solution: use Redis-backed sessions or JWT (stateless).

Master-worker communication uses IPC (inter-process communication) via `process.send()` and `process.on('message')`.

```typescript
import cluster from 'cluster';
import os from 'os';
import http from 'http';

if (cluster.isPrimary) {
  const numCPUs = os.cpus().length;
  console.log(`Primary ${process.pid} forking ${numCPUs} workers`);

  for (let i = 0; i < numCPUs; i++) cluster.fork();

  cluster.on('exit', (worker, code, signal) => {
    console.error(`Worker ${worker.process.pid} died (code ${code})`);
    cluster.fork(); // auto-restart
  });

  // IPC: broadcast a config update to all workers
  function broadcastConfig(config: object) {
    for (const id in cluster.workers) {
      cluster.workers[id]?.send({ type: 'config', payload: config });
    }
  }
} else {
  process.on('message', (msg: { type: string; payload: unknown }) => {
    if (msg.type === 'config') applyConfig(msg.payload);
  });

  http.createServer((req, res) => res.end(`Worker ${process.pid}`)).listen(3000);
}
```

**Common interview trap:** Candidates say clustering makes the app "multi-threaded." It doesn't — it creates multiple single-threaded processes. Each worker still blocks on synchronous code. Also: `cluster.isMaster` is deprecated in Node.js 16+ in favour of `cluster.isPrimary`.

