### Async Error Handling in Express: Why async Throws Don't Reach Error Middleware

In Express 4, route handlers are called synchronously. If you throw inside an `async` function, Express has no way to intercept that rejection — it unwinds the async stack, not the Express middleware stack. The rejection becomes an unhandledRejection and crashes Node.js 15+.

Express 5 (available as beta) wraps async handlers automatically. For Express 4, you need a wrapper.

```typescript
import { Request, Response, NextFunction, RequestHandler } from 'express';

// Wrapper to catch async errors and forward to Express error middleware
function asyncHandler(fn: RequestHandler): RequestHandler {
  return (req, res, next) => {
    Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next);
  };
}

// Without wrapper — ERROR: unhandled rejection crashes Node 15+
app.get('/bad', async (req, res) => {
  throw new Error('This bypasses Express error middleware!');
});

// With wrapper — correctly forwarded to error middleware
app.get('/users/:id', asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
  const user = await db.users.findById(req.params.id);
  if (!user) throw Object.assign(new Error('Not found'), { statusCode: 404 });
  res.json(user);
}));

// Centralised error handler receives the thrown error
app.use((err: Error & { statusCode?: number }, req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
  res.status(err.statusCode || 500).json({ error: err.message });
});
```

**Common interview trap:** Candidates say "Express catches async errors" — it doesn't in v4. They also confuse `next(err)` (forwards error) with `next()` (goes to next middleware). A subtle bug: if you call `res.json()` AND throw after it, the error middleware runs but the response is already sent — Express logs "Cannot set headers after they are sent."

