### Express Middleware: next() Semantics and Async Middleware Patterns

`next()` has three distinct call signatures with different effects: `next()` advances to the next matching middleware; `next('route')` skips remaining handlers on the current route, jumping to the next route; `next(error)` (any non-string truthy argument) jumps directly to error-handling middleware, bypassing all remaining regular middleware.

A common production pattern is wrapping all route handlers with an async error catcher to avoid repeated try-catch blocks.

```typescript
import { Request, Response, NextFunction, RequestHandler } from 'express';

// Global async wrapper
const wrap = (fn: RequestHandler): RequestHandler =>
  (req, res, next) => Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next);

// Validation middleware — short-circuits chain on invalid input
const validateBody = (schema: ZodSchema): RequestHandler =>
  (req, res, next) => {
    const result = schema.safeParse(req.body);
    if (!result.success) {
      return next(Object.assign(new Error('Validation failed'), {
        statusCode: 400,
        details: result.error.flatten(),
      }));
    }
    req.body = result.data; // replace with parsed/typed body
    next();
  };

app.post(
  '/users',
  validateBody(createUserSchema),
  wrap(async (req, res) => {
    const user = await userService.create(req.body);
    res.status(201).json(user);
  })
);

// next('route') example: skip to next route match
app.get('/items/:id', (req, res, next) => {
  if (req.params.id === 'new') return next('route'); // skip to next GET /items/:id
  res.json({ item: req.params.id });
});
app.get('/items/:id', (req, res) => res.render('new-item-form'));
```

**Common interview trap:** Calling `next()` after sending a response. Express won't throw immediately, but the next middleware will attempt to use `res` after it's already been sent, causing "Cannot set headers after they are sent." Guard with `if (res.headersSent) return;` in middleware that might run after the response.

