### Worker Threads vs Clustering

Worker Threads (worker_threads module) enable true multithreading within a single process, sharing memory via SharedArrayBuffer and other mechanisms. Each worker has its own event loop and V8 instance but shares the same heap segments. Clustering (cluster module) spawns separate processes, each with its own V8 instance and event loop, communicating via IPC.

Worker Threads suit CPU-intensive tasks like crypto or data processing due to lower overhead. Clustering is better for I/O-bound workloads as it provides natural isolation and fault recovery. Worker Threads require careful synchronization to avoid data races; clustering is inherently safer.

```typescript
import { Worker } from 'worker_threads';

const worker = new Worker('./worker.js');
worker.on('message', (msg) => {
  console.log(`Result: ${msg}`);
});
worker.postMessage({ data: 100 });

// worker.js:
import { parentPort } from 'worker_threads';
parentPort.on('message', (msg) => {
  const result = msg.data * 2;
  parentPort.postMessage(result);
});
```


**Common interview trap:** Candidates assume Worker Threads are always faster—they have initialization overhead. For small tasks, they may be slower than main thread execution. Also, debugging multithreaded code is harder.

